{{Primary sources|date=September 2017}}
'''Compassion focused therapy''' ('''CFT''') is a system of [[psychotherapy]] developed by [[Paul Gilbert (psychologist)|Paul Gilbert]] that integrates techniques from [[cognitive behavioral therapy]] with concepts from [[evolutionary psychology]], [[social psychology]], [[developmental psychology]], [[Buddhist psychology]], and [[neuroscience]]. "One of its key concerns is to use compassionate mind training to help people develop and work with experiences of inner warmth, safeness and soothing, via [[compassion]] and self-compassion."<ref name="Gilbert2009">{{harvnb|Gilbert|2009|p=199}}</ref>

The central therapeutic technique of CFT is compassionate mind training, which teaches the skills and attributes of [[compassion]].<ref>{{harvnb|Gilbert|2010b}}</ref> Compassionate mind training helps transform problematic patterns of cognition and emotion related to [[anxiety]], [[anger]], [[shame]], [[self-criticism]], [[depersonalization]], and [[hypomania]].<ref>{{harvnb|Gilbert|2009|p=208}}</ref>

Biological evolution forms the theoretical backbone of CFT. Humans have evolved with at least three primal types of emotion regulation system: the threat (protection) system, the drive (resource-seeking) system, and the soothing system.<ref>{{harvnb|Gilbert|2009|p=200}}; {{harvnb|Gilbert|2010a|p=43}}</ref> CFT emphasizes the links between cognitive patterns and these three emotion regulation systems.<ref>{{harvnb|Gilbert|2010a|p=59}}</ref> Through the use of techniques such as compassionate mind training and [[cognitive behavioral therapy]] (CBT), psychotherapy clients can learn to manage each system more effectively and respond more appropriately to situations.<ref>{{harvnb|Gilbert|2010c}}</ref> There are an increasing number of empirical research papers that demonstrate the importance of compassion as a way of directing behavior to deal with threat and resolve conflict.<ref>For example: {{harvnb|MacBeth|Gumley|2012}}; {{harvnb|Van Dam|Sheppard|Forsyth|Earleywine|2011}}</ref>

Compassion focused therapy is especially appropriate for people who have high levels of shame and self-criticism and who have difficulty in feeling warmth toward, and being kind to, themselves or others.<ref name="Gilbert2009"/> Such problems of shame and self-criticism are often rooted in a history of abuse, bullying, neglect, and/or lack of affection in the family.<ref>{{harvnb|Kaufman|1989}}; {{harvnb|Schore|1998}}</ref> CFT can help such people learn to feel more safeness and warmth in their interactions with others and themselves.<ref name="Gilbert2009"/>

Numerous methods are used in CFT to develop a person's compassion. For example, people undergoing CFT are taught to understand compassion from the third person, before transferring these thought processes to themselves.<ref>{{harvnb|Gilbert|Irons|2013|p=317}}</ref>

