{{Too technical|date=April 2018}} {{Infobox medical condition (new) | name = <!--{{PAGENAME}} by default--> | synonym = | image = | image_size = | alt = | caption = | pronounce = | specialty = <!-- from Wikidata, can be overwritten --> | symptoms = | complications = | onset = | duration = | types = | causes = | risks = | diagnosis = | differential = | prevention = | treatment = | medication = | prognosis = | frequency = | deaths = }} '''Florid cutaneous papillomatosis''' (FCP), also known as '''Schwartz-Burgess syndrome''', is an obligate [[paraneoplastic syndrome]].
FCP begins as the sudden onset of numerous [[papillomas|cutaneous papillomas]] that are clinically indistinguishable from [[viral warts]]. The papillomas range from 1 to 3&nbsp;mm in diameter may spread to involve the entire body, including the face. Pruritus, which may sometimes precede the onset of FCP, is evident in the affected regions in about half of patients. Evaluation of a [[skin biopsy]] clearly distinguishes FCP from viral warts.
FCP is associated with underlying cancer of the [[breast cancer|breast]], [[bladder cancer|bladder]], [[ovarian cancer|ovary]], [[uterine cancer|uterus]], [[prostate cancer|prostate]], and [[lung cancer|lung]]. Other associated underlying malignancies include [[squamous cell carcinomas]] and [[lymphomas]] such as [[non-Hodgkin's lymphoma]].
FCP is sometimes seen together with other signs of internal cancer, especially [[malignant acanthosis nigricans]], [[tripe palms]], [[Leser–Trélat sign]], and [[hypertrichosis lanuginosa acquisita]]. FCP tends to improve in association with surgical or chemotherapeutic therapy of the underlying internal cancer. A recurrence or exacerbation of FCP may be linked with tumor regrowth or metastatic spread.
==Signs and symptoms== The characteristic eruption is of multiple warty papules and nodules beginning on acral skin, especially the hands and wrists, and disseminating onto the skin of the entire body. These [[skin lesion]]s develop on the trunk, extremities, and face.<ref name="Mansouri">{{cite journal |author=Mansouri, P.|title=Florid cutaneous papillomatosis, malignant acanthosis nigrica, palmoplantar keratoderma, and gastric adenocarcinoma |journal=Acta Medical Iranica |volume=37 |issue=1 |year=1999 |url=http://journals.tums.ac.ir/upload_files/pdf/4884.pdf |format=PDF|display-authors=etal}}</ref>{{rp|63}} Pruritus is also associated.
==Causes== The etiology of florid cutaneous papillomatosis is unknown. It is likely directly induced by an underlying neoplasm secreting a growth factor. One candidate may be alpha-transforming growth factor, structurally related to epidermal growth factor, but antigenically distinct from it. The underlying cancer is most often [[gastric adenocarcinoma]]<ref name="Mansouri"/>{{rp|63}}<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.4103/0378-6323.16238 |author=Singhi, M.K.|title=Florid cutaneous papillomatosis with adenocarcinoma of stomach in a 35 year old male |journal=Indian J Dermatol Venereol Leprol |volume=71 |issue=3 |pages=195–6 |year=2005 |url=https://tspace.library.utoronto.ca/bitstream/1807/5515/1/dv05062.pdf |format=PDF |pmid=16394412|display-authors=etal}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | last1 = Klieb | first1 = HB. | last2 = Avon | first2 = SL. | last3 = Gilbert | first3 = J. | last4 = Sade | first4 = S. | last5 = Enepekides | first5 = D. | title = Florid cutaneous and mucosal papillomatosis: mucocutaneous markers of an underlying gastric malignancy. | journal = J Clin Oncol | volume = 31 | issue = 13 | pages = e218-9 |date=May 2013 | doi = 10.1200/JCO.2012.45.2151 | PMID = 23530104 }}</ref> but also with [[breast cancer]], [[bladder cancer]], [[hepatobiliary cancer]], [[ovarian cancer]], [[uterine cancer]],<ref>{{cite journal |author=Yoon Oo Noh, G.C.L. |author2=Mi Kyeong Kim |author3=Youn Soo Kim |author4=Tae Young Yoon |title=A Case of Florid Cutaneous Papillomatosis and Tripe Palm |journal=Korean J Dermatol |volume=7 |issue=40 |year=2002 |url=http://koreamed.org/SearchBasic.php?RID=291794&DT=1&QY=A+%5BALL%5D+Case+%5BALL%5D+Florid+%5BALL%5D+Cutaneous+%5BALL%5D+Papillomatosis+%5BALL%5D+Tripe+%5BALL%5D+Palm+%5BALL%5D}}</ref> [[prostate cancer]]{{Citation needed|date=March 2009}}, [[lung cancer]]<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1046/j.1468-3083.2000.00051.x |vauthors=Bottoni U, Dianzani C, Pranteda G, etal |title=Florid cutaneous and mucosal papillomatosis with acanthosis nigricans revealing a primary lung cancer |journal=J Eur Acad Dermatol Venereol |volume=14 |issue=3 |pages=205–8 |date=May 2000 |pmid=11032067 |url=http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/resolve/openurl?genre=article&sid=nlm:pubmed&issn=0926-9959&date=2000&volume=14&issue=3&spage=205}}</ref> and [[cervical cancer]].<ref>{{Citation | title = The Combination of Tripe Palms, Acanthosis Nigricans and Florid Cutaneous Papillomatosis in a Patient with Metastatic Cervical Cancer | year = 2004 | journal = Dermatol Sin | pages = 142–147 | volume = 22 | last1 = Tsai | first1 = Yu-Ju | last2 = Tsai | first2 = Yi-Jeng | last3 = Chuan | first3 = Ming-Tuo | last4 = Hu | first4 = Shu-Ling }}</ref> Other associated underlying malignancies include [[squamous cell carcinoma]]s and [[lymphoma]]s.<ref name="JanierBlanchet-Bardon1988">{{cite journal|last1=Janier|first1=M.|last2=Blanchet-Bardon|first2=C.|last3=Bonvalet|first3=D.|last4=Lenoble|first4=M.|last5=Boiget|first5=F.|last6=Civatte|first6=J.|title=Malignant Acanthosis nigricans Associated with Non-Hodgkin&rsquo;s Lymphoma|journal=Dermatology|volume=176|issue=3|year=1988|pages=133–137|issn=1421-9832|doi=10.1159/000248689}}</ref>
==Pathophysiology== Florid cutaneous papillomatosis, malignant acanthosis nigricans, and the sign of Leser-Trélat may be highlighted as part of a continuum, with each having a common or similar pathogenic pathway due to an underlying malignancy that produces a factor epidermal growth factor-like activity.{{citation needed|date=June 2017}}
==Diagnosis== The sudden eruption of papulonodules usually indistinguishable from common viral warts should suggest this diagnosis. These papulonodules begin on the extremities, especially on the dorsa of the hands and the wrists and may disseminate to involve the entire body, including the face.<ref name="LevineLevine2004">{{cite book|author1=Norman Levine|author2=Carol C. Levine|title=Dermatology Therapy. A - Z Essentials|date=12 February 2004|publisher=Springer|isbn=978-3-540-00864-4|page=242}}</ref> The papulonodules may vary in size from 2–3&nbsp;mm to 10&nbsp;mm in diameter. Pruritus is often associated.
Florid cutaneous papillomatosis is linked with an underlying cancer. Malignant acanthosis nigricans may also become evident, many times with the sudden eruption of multiple seborrheic keratoses, known as the sign of Leser-Trélat.<ref name="LebwohlHeymann2009">{{cite book|author1=Mark G. Lebwohl|author2=Warren R. Heymann|author3=John Berth-Jones|author4=Ian Coulson|title=Treatment of Skin Disease: Comprehensive Therapeutic Strategies|date=8 December 2009|publisher=Elsevier Health Sciences|isbn=978-0-7020-4328-4|page=88}}</ref><ref name="CollierLongmore2013">{{cite book|author1=Judith Collier|author2=Murray Longmore|author3=Keith Amarakone|title=Oxford Handbook of Clinical Specialties|date=31 January 2013|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-959118-3|page=589}}</ref><ref name="YarbroWujcik2010">{{cite book|author1=Connie Henke Yarbro|author2=Debra Wujcik|author3=Barbara Holmes Gobel|title=Cancer Nursing: Principles and Practice|date=15 November 2010|publisher=Jones & Bartlett Publishers|isbn=978-1-4496-5781-9|page=1902}}</ref> Florid cutaneous papillomatosis mandates a search for an underlying malignancy, recognizing that it may be seen in patients with multiple visceral carcinomas. Histologic examination shows uniform and pronounced hyperkeratosis, acanthosis, and papillomatosis without epidermal vacuolization, parakeratosis, or eosinophilic inclusions suggestive of viral warts.<ref name="WeedonStrutton1997">{{cite book|author1=David Weedon|author2=Geoffrey Strutton|title=Skin pathology|year=1997|publisher=Churchill Livingstone|isbn=978-0-443-05575-1|page=640}}</ref>
The sudden quality of the eruption of florid cutaneous papillomatosis and its anatomic distribution should facilitate distinction from widespread common warts and from epidermodysplasia verruciformis.
==Treatment== Identifying and treatment the underlying malignancy constitutes an uptime approach. [[5-fluorouracil|Topical 5-fluorouracil]] may occasionally be help, as may [[retinoid|oral retinoid]]s, [[topical steroid]]s, [[vitamin A acid]], [[urea]], [[salicylic acid]], [[podophyllotoxin]], and [[liquid nitrogen|cryodestruction employing liquid]].
==Prognosis== Improvement usually parallels that of the cancer, whether [[surgery|surgical]] or [[chemotherapy|chemotherapeutic]]. Generalization of the associated visceral malignancy may worsen the eruption.
==Epidemiology== Florid cutaneous papillomatosis is almost twice as common in men than in women, and is usually diagnosed in individuals aged 53–72 years (mean patient age, 58.5 years).<ref name="Mansouri" />{{rp|66}}
== History == Florid cutaneous papillomatosis was discovered by [[Robert A. Schwartz]] and [[Gordon H. Burgess]].<ref name="ChouYeh2012">{{cite journal|last1=Chou|first1=Che-Yi|last2=Yeh|first2=Shih-Wei|title=Multiple brownish warty papulonodules on left dorsal hand|journal=Dermatologica Sinica|volume=30|issue=2|year=2012|pages=81–82|issn=1027-8117|doi=10.1016/j.dsi.2011.10.004}}</ref> The original description was published in the ''Archives of Dermatology'',<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1001/archderm.114.12.1803 |vauthors=Schwartz RA, Burgess GH |title=Florid cutaneous papillomatosis |journal=Arch Dermatol |volume=114 |issue=12 |pages=1803–6 |date=December 1978 |pmid=153731 |url=http://archderm.ama-assn.org/cgi/pmidlookup?view=long&pmid=153731}} </ref> which is published by [[American Medical Association]]. It has since been called the Schwartz-Burgess syndrome.<ref name="Yang-2013">{{Cite journal | last1 = Yang | first1 = YH. | last2 = Zhang | first2 = RZ. | last3 = Kang | first3 = DH. | last4 = Zhu | first4 = WY. | title = Three paraneoplastic signs in the same patient with gastric adenocarcinoma. | journal = Dermatol Online J | volume = 19 | issue = 7 | pages = 18966 | year = 2013 | doi = | PMID = 24010512 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Gao|first1=Xing-Hua|last2=Chen|first2=Hong-Duo|title=Professor Robert A. Schwartz Awarded Title of Honorary Professor, China Medical University, Shenyang, November 20, 2012|journal=International Journal of Dermatology|volume=52|issue=2|year=2013|pages=262–262|issn=0011-9059|doi=10.1111/ijd.12131_2}}</ref>
==Society and culture== Patients may have their unaesthetic appearance resulting in [[social exclusion|isolation from their community]], feeling or being unwelcome in public places.<ref name="Csete-2005">{{Cite journal | last1 = Csete | first1 = B. | last2 = Moezzi | first2 = M. | last3 = Lengyel | first3 = Z. | last4 = Hodosi | first4 = B. | last5 = Zombai | first5 = E. | last6 = Battyáni | first6 = Z. | title = Florid cutaneous papillomatosis leading to social exclusion. | journal = Br J Dermatol | volume = 153 | issue = 3 | pages = 667–9 |date=Sep 2005 | doi = 10.1111/j.1365-2133.2005.06772.x | PMID = 16120165 }}</ref>
