{{Infobox hospital | Name = OSF Saint Anthony Medical Center | Org/Group = [[OSF Healthcare|OSF HealthCare]] | Image = <!-- optional --> | Caption = <!-- optional --> | Logo = | Region = [[Rockford, Illinois|Rockford]] | State = Illinois | Country = US | HealthCare = Private | Type = Teaching | Speciality = <!-- if devoted to a speciality, i.e. not if has broad spectrum of specialities --> | Standards = <!-- optional if no national standards --> | Emergency = I | Affiliation= [[University of Illinois College of Medicine|University of Illinois College of Medicine at Rockford]], [[Saint Anthony College of Nursing]] | Beds = 254 | Founded = August 18, 1899 | Closed = <!-- optional --> | Website = http://www.osfhealth.com/ | Wiki-Links = <!-- optional --> |}}
'''OSF Saint Anthony Medical Center''' is a hospital located in [[Rockford, Illinois]], USA. The medical center is part of the [[OSF Healthcare]] System.
==History== On July 1, 1899, six of the [[Sisters of the Third Order of St. Francis]] moved to Rockford at the request of the citizens to open a hospital.<ref name="OSFhis">[http://www.franciscansisterspeoria.org/history.htm History of the Sisters of the Third Order of St. Francis]</ref> The order had previously moved to America from [[Prussia]] in 1875, when [[Otto von Bismarck]] banned religious orders from the country.<ref name="OSFhis"/> With the help of the real estate agent William Crotty, the sisters were able to purchase a house on the corner of East State St. and Summit St. Community members donated the supplies and furniture for the first hospital.<ref name="history">[http://www.osfhealth.com/history.html OSF Saint Anthony Medical Center History]</ref>
==Services== OSF Saint Anthony Medical Center operates a [[Level I trauma center]]. OSF Saint Anthony Medical Center's Trauma Center is the only one in Rockford verified by the American College of Surgeons.<ref>https://www.facs.org/search/trauma-centers?state=IL&city=Rockford</ref> The emergency department has 19 rooms with a total of 24 beds.<ref>[http://www.osfhealth.com/emergency.html Emergency department]</ref> Since 1981, the Lifeline Emergency Helicopter Service has been based at Saint Anthony. The medical center also operates Rockford Cardiovascular Associates.<ref>https://www.osfhealthcare.org/practices/32/556/rockford-cardiovascular-associates</ref><ref>[http://www.osfhealth.com/cancer.html Center for Cancer Care]</ref> The Illinois Neurosciences Institute is located at the medical center.<ref>[http://www.osfhealth.com/neuro.html Illinois Neurosciences Institute]</ref> OSF SAMC surgeons perform 60% of open heart surgery cases in Rockford, making OSF SAMC the community leader in open heart surgery.
==Awards== In 2005, the [[American Nurses Credentialing Center]] awarded OSF the center "Magnet" status,<ref name="history"/><ref>[http://www.nursecredentialing.org/magnet/searchmagnet.cfm?searchoption=1&state=IL ANCC Magnet designation]</ref> the highest national recognition of nursing excellence that a hospital can receive.
